00:04:21.360 --> 00:04:23.720
So I would say George,
they would say Washington.

00:04:23.720 --> 00:04:26.950
I would say John, Adams, Thomas,
Jefferson, James, Madison, James,

00:04:26.950 --> 00:04:30.930
Monroe and we would go through
and halfway through you get

00:04:30.930 --> 00:04:32.890
to this wonderful anomaly

00:04:32.890 --> 00:04:35.170
which always delighted
them as they remembered.

00:04:35.170 --> 00:04:38.360 position:56%
In the beginning I would tell them
stories about each of the presidents

00:04:38.360 --> 00:04:42.680
or just say who was next and
some important circumstance.

00:04:42.680 --> 00:04:47.640
But when you get to Grover
Cleveland, Benjamin Harrison,

00:04:47.640 --> 00:04:53.630
Grover Cleveland again, and each
daughter, one is now turning 35,

00:04:53.630 --> 00:04:57.050 position:56%
when she first memorized it, when
we finished it I said you know what,

00:04:57.050 --> 00:05:01.060
Sarah, we should write
a children's book.

00:05:01.060 --> 00:05:03.640
That was 30 years ago.

00:05:03.640 --> 00:05:07.100
Her sister, four years
younger, Lilly, same thing,

00:05:07.100 --> 00:05:08.590
I said we should do
a children's book.

00:05:08.590 --> 00:05:10.980
I'm really serious this time.

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:16.150
Olivia, who was 11 six years
ago, committed all the presidents

00:05:16.150 --> 00:05:20.330
to memory that way and I said now
it's time actually to do something.

00:05:20.330 --> 00:05:24.130
And my youngest, Willow, who's 5,
the same age as my granddaughter

00:05:24.130 --> 00:05:28.440
who I haven't yet drilled the
presidents on, she did it.

00:05:28.440 --> 00:05:32.180
And if you go to the Random
House Children's Book website

00:05:32.180 --> 00:05:35.150
and look this up you
will see Willow Burns,

00:05:35.150 --> 00:05:37.860
age 5, reciting the presidents.

00:05:37.860 --> 00:05:39.660
Which means anybody can do it.

00:05:39.660 --> 00:05:43.680
But the idea was to originally
do kind of an [inaudible],

00:05:43.680 --> 00:05:46.490
something that would just
be presidents to memorize.

00:05:46.490 --> 00:05:50.330
But as we got into it we realized
that these were all human beings

00:05:50.330 --> 00:05:53.420
and somehow that they had
been placed at and removed

00:05:53.420 --> 00:05:55.210
from us, put up on pedestals.

00:05:55.210 --> 00:05:57.120
They were no longer human beings.

00:05:57.120 --> 00:06:01.070
They were the sum total of their
successes or their mistakes.

00:06:01.070 --> 00:06:04.250
And these were all people who
had parents, who had siblings

00:06:04.250 --> 00:06:08.740
for the most point, who had pets,
who had hobbies, who had kids,

00:06:08.740 --> 00:06:11.440
and that it was important
to humanize them.

00:06:11.440 --> 00:06:15.070
And so the book became you know
richer and richer and denser

00:06:15.070 --> 00:06:19.640
and denser in that so that
like a kind of Grand Canyon

00:06:19.640 --> 00:06:22.460
of many layers it's
possible to just use it

00:06:22.460 --> 00:06:25.810
to help you memorize the presidents
and know what the number is.

00:06:25.810 --> 00:06:28.830
Abraham Lincoln, by the way, is 16.

00:06:28.830 --> 00:06:33.170
That it was also possible to learn
a little bit more about them.

00:06:33.170 --> 00:06:36.710
And so we have what we call the
baseball card, the information

00:06:36.710 --> 00:06:39.150 position:56%
of when they were born, when they
died, when their administration was,

00:06:39.150 --> 00:06:42.620
their brothers, their sisters,
but then a large section

00:06:42.620 --> 00:06:45.840
that would be helpful for kids
a little bit older writing book

00:06:45.840 --> 00:06:49.440 position:56%
reports and even older than that
writing more extensive book reports.

00:06:49.440 --> 00:06:54.950
And so we think we have, as Random
House calls it, Knopf calls it,

00:06:54.950 --> 00:06:56.660
a treasury of the America.

00:06:56.660 --> 00:06:58.750
That this is something
that you could hold on to

00:06:58.750 --> 00:07:00.900
and last for a long time.

00:07:00.900 --> 00:07:02.380
&gt;&gt; Sam Litzinger: Part of
the problem for a historian

00:07:02.380 --> 00:07:04.230
or a documentarian or a writer

00:07:04.230 --> 00:07:07.140
in general it seems is
knowing what to leave out.

00:07:07.140 --> 00:07:08.440
&gt;&gt; Ken Burns: Yes.

00:07:08.440 --> 00:07:10.520
&gt;&gt; Sam Litzinger: This book
could have been 1200 pages long.

00:07:10.520 --> 00:07:14.300
&gt;&gt; Ken Burns: You know it's pretty
interesting, this took a lot longer

00:07:14.300 --> 00:07:16.440
than I thought it would take.

00:07:16.440 --> 00:07:18.900
It was a lot harder than
I thought it would be.

00:07:18.900 --> 00:07:22.600
I'm used to working on
projects for many, many years.

00:07:22.600 --> 00:07:26.120 position:56%
I have a film on the history of the
Vietnam War that's coming out a year

00:07:26.120 --> 00:07:28.460
from now and when it comes
out I will have worked

00:07:28.460 --> 00:07:30.070
on it more than 10 years.

00:07:30.070 --> 00:07:31.600
So we're used to that.

00:07:31.600 --> 00:07:36.100
But I had thought that you could
just scoop in and you can't.

00:07:36.100 --> 00:07:39.750
You have to do as much work
for this book as you had to do

00:07:39.750 --> 00:07:41.690
for even a biography
of the president.

00:07:41.690 --> 00:07:45.550
And we had it vetted by a number
of distinguished historians who do,

00:07:45.550 --> 00:07:51.380
are great, great happiness said, I
learned stuff that I didn't know.

00:07:51.380 --> 00:07:54.830
And they're folks who have spent
their lives studying the presidency

00:07:54.830 --> 00:07:57.430
and writing, you know, big,
huge, thick books about it.

00:07:57.430 --> 00:08:00.570
So in order to figure
out what to leave out,

00:08:00.570 --> 00:08:03.030
you know I live in New Hampshire.

00:08:03.030 --> 00:08:04.330
We make maple syrup there.

00:08:04.330 --> 00:08:08.910
And it takes 40 gallons of sap to
make one gallon of maple syrup.

00:08:08.910 --> 00:08:13.420
And I'm sure the amount of
material that we collected for each

00:08:13.420 --> 00:08:17.720
of these presidents was at least 40
