00:13:02.050 --> 00:13:03.870 position:56%
and evergreen nature to the stories.

00:13:03.870 --> 00:13:06.810
I mean mostly when you say
documentary most people think

00:13:06.810 --> 00:13:09.540
of people who are advocating
a particular point of view,

00:13:09.540 --> 00:13:13.550
exposing something that's
very relative in that moment.

00:13:13.550 --> 00:13:15.900
But quite often history
is addressing all

00:13:15.900 --> 00:13:20.370 position:56%
of the same issues we're addressing
today but it's doing it about events

00:13:20.370 --> 00:13:23.890
that took place seemingly before
and unrelated to us but are

00:13:23.890 --> 00:13:26.380
so resonant with human nature.

00:13:26.380 --> 00:13:27.720
History doesn't repeat itself.

00:13:27.720 --> 00:13:30.150
We're not condemned to
repeat what we don't remember

00:13:30.150 --> 00:13:32.220
but human nature never changes.

00:13:32.220 --> 00:13:36.000
And understanding the patterns
and the themes and the motif

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.290
of the past arm you in
the best possible way

00:13:38.290 --> 00:13:39.800
to understand the present.

00:13:39.800 --> 00:13:42.370
You know Ecclesiastes
said it better than me,

00:13:42.370 --> 00:13:45.970
what has been will be again, what
has been done will be done again.

00:13:45.970 --> 00:13:48.170
There's nothing new under the sun.

00:13:48.170 --> 00:13:51.620
And that means that human
nature super imposes itself

00:13:51.620 --> 00:13:54.250
over the random chaos of events

00:13:54.250 --> 00:13:57.440
and we can perceive those
patterns and that's what we do.

00:13:57.440 --> 00:13:59.090
Mark Twain is supposed to have said

00:13:59.090 --> 00:14:02.220
that history doesn't
repeat itself but it rhymes.

00:14:02.220 --> 00:14:06.110
[laughter] And it's a wonderful
phrase if in fact he did say it.

00:14:06.110 --> 00:14:10.140
But I spent my entire
professional life, 40 years,

00:14:10.140 --> 00:14:12.870
trying to hear those rhymes,
trying to hear that stuff.

00:14:12.870 --> 00:14:16.610
And so quite often when you take
a subject that seems safely,

00:14:16.610 --> 00:14:19.750
distantly in the past it
is resonant with today.

00:14:19.750 --> 00:14:23.720
I'll give you a simple example,
our recent film this past spring

00:14:23.720 --> 00:14:27.150
on Jackie Robinson, which
was sort of exploding some

00:14:27.150 --> 00:14:30.720
of the sentimental myths about him
and telling a much more dynamic

00:14:30.720 --> 00:14:35.460
and complicated person, is
speaking to the themes that are

00:14:35.460 --> 00:14:39.250
on the front page of today's
paper, about Black Lives Matter,

00:14:39.250 --> 00:14:41.850
about driving while black,
about stop and frisk,

00:14:41.850 --> 00:14:44.450
about integrated swimming
pools, about integration,

00:14:44.450 --> 00:14:49.730
about housing disparities, about
wage disparities, all of the things

00:14:49.730 --> 00:14:52.040
that are still omnipresent
in our discussion

00:14:52.040 --> 00:14:55.660
about race today are happening
in the context of a story

00:14:55.660 --> 00:14:59.970
that we've normally just
relegated to a happy story of a guy

00:14:59.970 --> 00:15:01.480
who turned the other cheek.

00:15:01.480 --> 00:15:03.920
He did and it's impressive
but the story

00:15:03.920 --> 00:15:06.330
of the real Jackie
Robinson is more important.

00:15:06.330 --> 00:15:09.460
That's why I think coming
to terms with these guys

00:15:09.460 --> 00:15:14.110
in a human dimension allows them
to remain fresh and new to us just

00:15:14.110 --> 00:15:16.750
as we deal with many
of the same themes.

00:15:16.750 --> 00:15:19.540
George Washington and Thomas
Jefferson were dealing

00:15:19.540 --> 00:15:23.350
with the same themes of race
we're dealing with today.

00:15:23.350 --> 00:15:25.300
&gt;&gt; Sam Litzinger: At a conversation
we are probably, are we ever going

00:15:25.300 --> 00:15:26.670
